article.description:
Tina Thompson and Janeth Arcain combined for 34
points to lead the Houston Comets to a 74-47 victory over the
Sacramento Monarchs on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Comets win ninth straight at home
article.linkText: Arcain, Thompson power Comets past Monarchs
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Tina Thompson and Janeth Arcain combined for 34
points to lead the Houston Comets to a 74-47 victory over the
Sacramento Monarchs on Tuesday night.

The Comets, which have won 10 of their last 12 games, improved
to 16-9 and moved within 1½ games of first-place Los Angeles in the
WNBA's Western Conference. The win was the Comets' ninth straight
at home.

Thompson scored 18 points on 7-for-12 shooting.

"We just played really well defensively," Thompson said.
"This was maybe our best game of the season. We just shocked them
early and they never really got things going. Maybe we weren't the
team that they were used to seeing in us."

Edna Campbell and Demya Walker each had nine points for the
Monarchs (14-13).

Yolanda Griffith, Sacramento's leading scorer, was held to seven
points on 2-for-6 shooting.

Of Houston, Sacramento coach John Whisenant said, "You've got
to really admire their fast start and how they came out tonight.
They had their game faces on even before the game started during
warm-ups."

Second-year center Michelle Snow set one franchise record and
tied another for Houston. With her third blocked shot Tuesday, she
set the Comets' season mark in that category with 47. Sheryl
Swoopes had 46 in 1999.

Snow also tied the franchise record with four consecutive games
with 10 or more rebounds, grabbing 11 Tuesday night. Thompson was
the last Comet to do it from June 2-10, 2001.

"It feels great to break records," Snow said. "But winning is
all I care about right now. We knew we had to come in ready to play
and that is why we never let up."

Houston shot 50 percent in the first half and took a 41-29 lead.

After Tangela Smith scored for Sacramento, the Comets used a
13-2 run to take a 13-4 lead 4:11 into the game. Sacramento used an
8-2 run to get within 31-25 with 4:23 left, but Houston responded
with 10-3 run to take a 13-point lead with 55 seconds left in the
half.

Houston opened the second half with a 10-4 run and went on to
lead by as many as 29 points.
